Day 2 — HTML File Structure & Basic CSS Styling

1. Creating an HTML File
Steps to Create an HTML File:

1. Open VS Code 
2. Create a new file
3. Save with .html extension
Ex:  index.html

2. Basic HTML Document Structure
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
<title>Document</title>
</head>
<body>
</body>
</html>

3. Meta Tags
Character Encoding:
<meta charset="UTF-8">

Responsive Design:
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">

4. Adding CSS Inside HTML (Internal CSS)

<style>
p {
    color: blue;
}
</style>
5. CSS Selectors
Element Selector Example:
p {
    color: blue;
}
Div Styling:
div {
    background-color: aqua;
}
Image Styling:
img {
    width: 400px;
}
6. Class and ID Attributes
Class Example:
<div class="div1">
CSS:
.div1 {
    background-color: yellow;
}
ID Example:
<div id="div2">
CSS:
#div2 {
    background-color: pink;
}
7. Adding Images
Local Image:
<img src="./sample.jpg" alt="">
Online Image:
<img src="https://example.com/image.jpg" alt="">
8. Complete Example
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<title>Day 2 Practice</title>
<style>
div{
    background-color:aqua;
}
p{
    color:blue;
}
img{
    width:400px;
}
</style>
</head>
<body>
<div class="div1">
    <h1>I am h1</h1>
    <h2>I am h2</h2>
</div>
<div id="div2">
    <h3>I am h3</h3>
    <h4>I am h4</h4>
</div>
<p>This is para 1</p>
<p>This is para 2</p>
<img src="./sample.jpg" alt="">
<img src="https://example.com/image.jpg" alt="">
</body>
</html>
Concepts Covered — Day 2
• Creating HTML files
• HTML page structure
• Meta tags
• Internal CSS
• CSS selectors
• Class & ID usage
• Adding local and online images
 

Day: 3
1. Margin vs Padding (The Box Model Basics)
+---------------------------+
|        Margin             |  ← space outside the box
|  +---------------------+  |
|  |      Border         |  |
|  |  +---------------+  |  |
|  |  |   Padding     |  |  | ← space inside the box
|  |  | +-----------+ |  |  |
|  |  | | Content   | |  |  |
|  |  | +-----------+ |  |  |
|  |  +---------------+  |  |
|  +---------------------+  |
+---------------------------+

Padding = Space inside the element

It pushes the content away from the border.

Margin = Space outside the element

It creates distance between this element and other elements.


2. Padding Example

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<style>
.box {
  background-color: lightblue;
  padding: 20px;
  border: 2px solid blue;
}
</style>
</head>
<body>

<div class="box">
  This text has padding around it.
</div>

</body>
</html>

You can also control sides individually:
padding-top: 10px;
padding-right: 20px;
padding-bottom: 10px;
padding-left: 20px;

padding: 10px 20px;  /* top-bottom | left-right */
padding: 10px 20px 30px 50px; 
padding: 10px 20px 30px 40px; /* top | right | bottom | left */

3. Margin Example
<style>
.box {
  background-color: lightgreen;
  padding: 10px;
  margin: 30px;
  border: 2px solid green;
}
</style>

<div class="box">Box 1</div>
<div class="box">Box 2</div>

You can also control sides individually:
margin-top: 10px;
margin-right: 20px;
margin-bottom: 10px;
margin-left: 20px;

margin: 20px;              /* all sides */
margin: 10px 30px;         /* top-bottom | left-right */
margin: 10px 20px 30px 40px; /* top | right | bottom | left */

Difference

| Property | Space Location | Use Case                         |
| -------- | -------------- | -------------------------------- |
| Padding  | Inside border  | Increase space around content    |
| Margin   | Outside border | Create distance between elements |

5. CSS Imports
<head>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="filename.css">
</head>

6. Usage of External Css File
External CSS means writing styles in a separate file (like style.css) and linking it to your HTML pages.
Easy Maintainence

Benefits:
1. Reuse Across Multiple Pages

One CSS file can style many pages.

If your site has:

home.html
contact.html

All can use the same style.css.
Result: Same design everywhere.

2. Easy Maintenance

If you want to change the heading color:
h1 {
  color: red;
}

3. Faster Loading

Browsers cache CSS files.
After first load, pages load faster.

4. Better Team Work

Designers work on CSS
Developers work on HTML/logic

<!-- index.html -->
 <head>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
</head>

<body>
  <h1>Welcome</h1>
  <p>This is a website.</p>
</body>

<!-- contact.html -->
 <!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">

<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Document</title>
    
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="main.css">
   
</head>

<body>
    <div id="padding-style">
        i am naveen
    </div>
</body>

</html>


2. Text Styling Properties in CSS

2.1 font-size

Controls the size of text.

p {
  font-size: 16px;
}

Other units:

px (pixels)
em
rem
%

Example:

h1 {
  font-size: 32px;
}

2.2 font-family

Controls the font style.

body {
  font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;
}

Always provide fallback fonts:

font-family:  serif;
Common families:
sans-serif (modern)
serif (traditional)
monospace (coding style)


2.3 font-weight
Controls thickness of text.

p {
  font-weight: bold;
}

Values:
normal
bold
lighter
bolder
Numbers: 100 to 900

Example:

h1 {
  font-weight: 700;
}


2.4 font-style

Controls italic text.

p {
  font-style: italic;
}

Values:
normal
italic
oblique


2.5 text-align

Controls alignment.

p {
  text-align: center;
}


Values:
left
right
center


2.6 text-decoration

Used for underline, remove link underline, etc.

a {
  text-decoration: none;
}

Values:
underline
none
line-through
overline


2.7 line-height

Controls space between lines.

p {
  line-height: 1.6;
}

Improves readability.


2.8 color

Changes text color.

h1 {
  color: red;
}

Also:
color: #333;
color: rgb(255, 0, 0);
color: blue;


3. Combined Example

HTML

<link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">

<h1 class="title">My Website</h1>
<p class="content">This is a sample paragraph.</p>


<!-- giving styles in css file -->
style.css
body {
  font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
}

.title {
  font-size: 32px;
  font-weight: bold;
  text-align: center;
  color: #2c3e50;
}

.content {
  font-size: 16px;
  line-height: 1.6;
  color: #555;
}



<!-- Day 3 – Flexbox & Media Queries -->
1️. Flexbox Layout
What is Flexbox?
Flexbox (Flexible Box Layout) is a CSS layout model used to:
a. Align items easily
b. Distribute space between elements
c. Build responsive layouts
d. Control row and column structures

<div class="container">
  <!-- inner blocks -->
</div>

.container {
  display: flex;
}

2️. Flex Direction – Row

By default, flex items are placed in a row (left to right).
Example:
<div class="container">
  <div class="box">Box 1</div>
  <div class="box">Box 2</div>
  <div class="box">Box 3</div>
</div>

.container {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: row;   /* default */
  gap: 10px;
}

.box {
  background-color: lightblue;
  padding: 20px;
  border: 1px solid blue;
}

3️. Flex Direction – Column

When we change direction to column, items stack vertically.
Usage:

.container {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  gap: 10px;
}

Output:

Box1
Box2
Box3

4️. Important Flexbox Properties

a. justify-content: center;

    <div class="center-space">
        <div>
            conatiner 1
        </div>
         <div>
            conatiner 2
        </div>
         <div>
            conatiner 3
        </div>
         <div>
            conatiner 4
        </div>
         <div>
            conatiner 5
        </div>
    </div>

.center-space {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: row;
  justify-content: center;
  align-items: center;
  gap: 20px;
  border: black 1px solid;
}

b. justify-content: space-between;

<div class="main">
        <div>
            conatiner 1
        </div>
         <div>
            conatiner 2
        </div>
         <div>
            conatiner 3
        </div>
         <div>
            conatiner 4
        </div>
         <div>
            conatiner 5
        </div>
</div>

.main {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: row;
  justify-content: space-between;
  align-items: center;
  border: black 1px solid;
}

c. justify-content: space-around;


    <div class="around-space">
        <div>
            conatiner 1
        </div>
         <div>
            conatiner 2
        </div>
         <div>
            conatiner 3
        </div>
         <div>
            conatiner 4
        </div>
         <div>
            conatiner 5
        </div>
    </div>

.around-space {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: row;
  justify-content: space-around;
  align-items: center;
  border: black 1px solid;
}


d. justify-content: space-evenly;

<div class="even-space">
        <div>
            conatiner 1
        </div>
         <div>
            conatiner 2
        </div>
         <div>
            conatiner 3
        </div>
         <div>
            conatiner 4
        </div>
         <div>
            conatiner 5
        </div>
    </div> 

    .even-space {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: row;
  justify-content: space-evenly;
  align-items: center;
  border: black 1px solid;
}

5. Media Queries (Responsiveness)

What is Responsiveness?
Responsiveness means:-
a. Website adjusts layout based on screen size
b. Works on mobile, tablet, desktop  


@media (max-width: 768px) {
  /* CSS for smaller screens */
}

@media (min-width: 768px) {
  /* CSS for smaller screens */
}

max-width → applies below this screen size
min-width → applies above this screen size 

Example:

    <div class="main">
        <div>
            conatiner 1
        </div>
         <div>
            conatiner 2
        </div>
         <div>
            conatiner 3
        </div>
         <div>
            conatiner 4
        </div>
         <div>
            conatiner 5
        </div>
    </div>


.main {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: row;
  justify-content: space-between;
  align-items: center;
  border: black 1px solid;
}


/* mobile devices/screens */
@media (max-width: 576px) {
  .main {
    background-color: aquamarine;
  }
}

/* tabs/ipads */
@media (min-width: 577px) and (max-width: 768px) {
  .main {
    display: block;
    background-color: blue;
  }
}

/* desktops/laptops/PCs */
@media (min-width:769px)  {
  .main{
    background-color: brown;
    display: block;
  }
}